description:
{
  "scene": "Alice stands between Tweedledee and Tweedledum, her hand raised to her mouth suppressing laughter. Tweedledee holds a sword and round shield/bolster, while Tweedledum carries a similar weapon, both in their rotund, comical forms wearing checkered trousers and hats. The setting is outdoors with foliage in the background.",
  "style": "Black and white halftone illustration in a realistic yet whimsical pen-and-ink style typical of early 20th century book illustration, signed by Peter Newell, likely from a 1900s edition of 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in image]\n\"Alice laughed loud; but she managed to turn it into a cough\" [caption below image]"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl (Alice) seated on grass, wearing a white dress and Mary Jane shoes, holding a crown on her head with both hands, looking surprised or puzzled. Roses are visible in the background. The scene depicts Alice discovering the crown on her head, from 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "style": "Pen and ink / wash illustration in a Victorian/Edwardian style, likely early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell, a known illustrator of the Alice books (1901 edition).",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in illustration]\n\"'And what is this on my head?' she exclaimed\""
}

{
  "scene": "Two fantastical creatures: a tall, thin bird-like creature wearing a white fedora hat with a black band, standing on long legs with human-like hands for feet, and a lion-like creature with spiky mane and small horns lying on the ground, biting or holding a stick/twig. Both creatures have exaggerated, comical expressions. The scene illustrates the Jubjub bird and the Bandersnatch from Lewis Carroll's 'Jabberwocky'.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash tones, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian era book illustration, circa early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [signature in image]\n\"'Beware the Jubjub bird, and shun\nThe frumious Bandersnatch!'\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress with a hair ribbon stands in a forest, her arms wrapped lovingly around the neck of a spotted fawn. The setting is dim and atmospheric with large tree trunks and foliage in the background. This depicts Alice from 'Through the Looking-Glass' embracing a Fawn in the wood where things have no names.",
  "style": "Pen and ink/watercolor illustration in a soft, romantic Victorian/Edwardian style, likely early 20th century (circa 1900-1910), characteristic of classic children's book illustration of that era.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"Alice with her arms clasped lovingly round the soft neck of the Fawn\""
}

{
  "scene": "Three figures dancing in a ring in a wooded setting: a girl with long dark hair wearing a white dress with a bow (seen from behind, likely Alice), flanked by two identical rotund figures wearing small top hats, white collars, and plaid trousers (Tweedledee and Tweedledum). They are holding hands and dancing in a circle.",
  "style": "Black and white halftone illustration in a Victorian/Edwardian children's book style, likely early 20th century, consistent with illustrations from Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass'.",
  "visible_text": "\"The next moment they were dancing round in a ring\""
}

{
  "scene": "A walrus wearing striped trousers leans over a bed in which an elderly oyster character lies with its shell-head on a pillow under a starfish-patterned blanket. An old man (the Carpenter) stands behind the walrus, looking on. The setting appears to be a seaside environment with waves in the background. This illustrates the poem 'The Walrus and the Carpenter' from Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass.'",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with tonal shading, characteristic of late 19th to early 20th century book illustration style, signed by Peter Newell, a well-known American illustrator of that era (circa 1900s).",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"'The eldest Oyster winked his eye,\nAnd shook his heavy head—'\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young elephant looming large in the foreground, viewed from a low angle, with its trunk curled downward toward small flowers and plants on the ground. In the background, two smaller elephants are visible in an open landscape. A large white lotus or water lily flower is prominent in the lower left.",
  "style": "Sepia-toned pen and ink or watercolor illustration in a classic early 20th century children's book style, likely 1900s–1920s, with detailed naturalistic rendering and soft tonal gradations. Artist signature visible lower right appears to read 'Peter...' (partially legible).",
  "visible_text": "\"In fact, it was an elephant—as Alice soon found out\""
}

{
  "scene": "A chaotic banquet scene showing a girl wearing a small crown (likely a queen figure, possibly Alice from Through the Looking-Glass) pulling or grasping a large white tablecloth as dishes, candles, candlesticks, and fantastical guests including animals and odd creatures come crashing down in a heap. The scene depicts the climactic dinner party collapse.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash tones, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa early 1900s. Likely by Peter Newell, whose signature appears in the lower right corner of the illustration.",
  "visible_text": "Caption below image: \"Dishes, guests, and candles came crashing down together in a heap on the floor\" | Artist signature in lower right corner of illustration: Peter Newell"
}

{
  "scene": "Three child-like figures wearing crowns are shown in a heap on grass; two larger figures flank a smaller central figure whose head appears to be rolling or fallen from her shoulders. A crown has fallen to the ground in the foreground. The caption describes heads rolling from a shoulder, suggesting this is a fantastical or dream-like scene likely from a Lewis Carroll-type narrative.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink or graphite illustration in a detailed, storybook style typical of late 19th to early 20th century book illustration. Signed by Peter Newell, a known illustrator of that era.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"First one round head, and then the other, rolled down from her shoulder\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress (Alice) runs frantically while being pulled by a regal, oddly-proportioned Queen figure wearing a crown and ornate robes, holding a scepter or wand. Both figures appear to be running at great speed, with the girl's hair and dress blown back by motion. The scene depicts the famous 'Now! Now! Faster! Faster!' running scene from Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass.'",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash toning, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell, known for his Alice in Wonderland illustrations.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature, lower right]\n\"'Now! Now!' cried the Queen. 'Faster! Faster!'\" [caption below illustration]"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl wearing a paper crown and holding a wand stands beside a large frog-like creature dressed in a jacket and breeches, who is bent forward examining or rubbing something on a wooden door. The scene appears to be outside a building with an arched doorway and trees in the background. A small flowering plant grows near the door.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash shading, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa early 1900s. The style is detailed and realistic with fine crosshatching.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"Then he went nearer and rubbed it with his thumb\""
}

{
  "scene": "A crowd scene featuring a large anthropomorphic hare/rabbit leaning toward a man in a top hat whose mouth is open as if speaking or being examined; the man holds a teacup. A girl in a pinafore stands to the left, and a chess piece (White King or similar) with a wide-eyed face appears to the right. Flags or spears are visible in the background. The caption identifies this as a scene where someone asks 'How are you, dear child?' — consistent with Alice Through the Looking-Glass.",
  "style": "Black-and-white pen-and-ink illustration with tonal wash, characteristic of early 20th-century American book illustration; signed by Peter Newell, who illustrated Lewis Carroll's Alice books around 1901–1902.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature, lower left]\n\"'How are you, dear child?' he went on\" [caption below illustration]"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress (Alice) bends down to speak to a White Knight or figure who appears to be upside-down or stooped near a horse laden with unusual equipment including what appears to be a basket and a horn/trumpet. They are in a forest setting on a path.",
  "style": "Black and white pen/ink illustration in a detailed Victorian/Edwardian style, typical of early 20th century book illustration, signed by Peter Newell, consistent with illustrations for Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass'.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in lower right of illustration]\n\"'How can you go on talking so quietly, head downward?'\""
}

{
  "scene": "Humpty Dumpty, depicted as a large egg-shaped figure with a human face, sits atop a brick wall leaning down toward a young girl with long dark hair (Alice) who reaches up toward him. Humpty Dumpty is grinning broadly. Garden plants and hollyhocks flank the wall.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash shading, characteristic of late 19th to early 20th century book illustration style. Signed by Peter Newell, consistent with his illustrations for Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass'.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature, lower left]\n\"And he grinned almost from ear to ear\" [caption below image]"
}

{
  "scene": "A anthropomorphized walrus wearing a striped outfit stands weeping (holding a handkerchief to its face) amid scattered oyster shells on a beach. Behind it, a human carpenter or tradesman figure sits holding food and looking guilty or uncomfortable. The walrus appears to be feigning sorrow over the eaten oysters.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a detailed, expressive late Victorian/Edwardian style, consistent with early 20th century book illustration. Signed by Peter Newell, a known illustrator of Lewis Carroll's works.",
  "visible_text": "'\"I weep for you,\" the Walrus said;\n\"I deeply sympathize\"'\n\nPeter Newell"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress (Alice) stands looking up at an elderly knight in armor seated on a white horse. The knight has a comical, gentle expression and is gesturing with one hand. Various objects hang from the saddle. The setting appears to be a forest path. This depicts the White Knight scene from Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass.'",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a detailed, expressive Victorian/Edwardian style, signed by Peter Newell, likely early 20th century (circa 1900-1910).",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in image]\n\"With a faint smile lighting up his gentle, foolish face, . . . he began\""
}

{
  "scene": "A fallen armored knight lying on the ground between the legs of a large horse, looking dazed and upward, while a young girl in a white apron dress bends over to look at him. The knight holds a small lance or stick, and wears spur-equipped boots. A large shield or armor piece is visible above.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with sepia wash tones, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration circa 1900-1910. Signed by Peter Newell, a known illustrator of Lewis Carroll's works.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [signature]\n\"'Plenty of practice!' he went on repeating, all the time\""
}

{
  "scene": "A dining table scene showing Alice (young girl with crown) seated between the Red Queen and White Queen (both wearing crowns), with a baboon-like figure behind them, and a leg of mutton standing upright in a large serving dish making a bow. Various table items including a covered dish, candelabra, and cutlery are visible.",
  "style": "Black and white pen and ink illustration in a detailed, whimsical Victorian/Edwardian style, signed by Peter Newell, likely early 1900s, consistent with illustrated editions of Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass'.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"The leg of mutton got up in the dish and made a little bow to Alice\""
}

{
  "scene": "Two figures — a young girl with long dark hair in a white dress (Alice) and a crowned queen-like figure holding a scepter — stand beside trees looking out over a vast landscape divided into a grid pattern resembling a giant chessboard. The scene depicts the moment Alice recognizes the land is laid out like a chess-board, from 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with detailed cross-hatching and tonal shading, characteristic of late 19th to early 20th century book illustration style. Signed by Peter Newell, an American illustrator active around 1900.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"'I declare it's marked out just like a large chess-board!' Alice said at last\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl (Alice) holds a platter with a dark cake and a knife toward a large lion who blinks lazily at her. Behind Alice stands a small crowned figure (the White King or a king character) with wide frightened eyes, and to the right is a unicorn dressed in human clothing with a belt and buckled shoes. Castle spires are visible in the background. The scene depicts the Lion and the Unicorn episode from 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "style": "Pen and ink illustration with wash/tonal shading, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell, a known illustrator of Alice in Wonderland editions.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"'What's this?' he said, blinking lazily at Alice\""
}

{
  "scene": "A small girl with long dark hair in a white dress leans over the bow of a rowboat, her arms plunged into the water elbow-deep. Behind her sits a large anthropomorphic sheep wearing a bonnet, glasses, and a floral dress, holding oars. The boat moves through choppy water near reeds or rushes. This illustrates a scene from Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass,' specifically the chapter where Alice rows with the Sheep.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with soft tonal shading, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"The little arms were plunged in elbow-deep\""
}

{
  "scene": "Humpty Dumpty, depicted as an egg-shaped figure wearing a cap and decorative belt, leans down from a wall to shout into the ear of a small boy wearing a beret with a feather. The boy stands with arms crossed and eyes closed, appearing to endure the shouting. Humpty Dumpty holds a small lantern or kettle. The scene illustrates a moment of loud, one-sided communication.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a classic early 20th century children's book style, characteristic of the Edwardian era. Signed by Peter Newell, known for his Alice in Wonderland illustrations.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"'I said it very loud and clear;\nI went and shouted in his ear'\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress kneeling on a rug, leaning forward toward a small black kitten that sits facing a tiny chess piece (likely a queen). Behind her to the left are two other cats, one black and one white. The setting appears to be a domestic interior with furniture visible in the background. The girl appears delighted or triumphant.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with tonal shading, late Victorian/Edwardian era, consistent with book illustration style of the early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature within image]; \"'Now, Kitty!' she cried, clapping her hands triumphantly\" [caption below image]"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl (Alice) sits at a counter/table across from an anthropomorphized old Sheep dressed in a floral gown, bonnet, and spectacles, sitting in an arm-chair and knitting with many needles. A basket of eggs/balls sits on the counter. Shelves with toys and items are visible in the background. A small drum or stool is near the Sheep's feet.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration, detailed cross-hatching, Victorian/Edwardian book illustration style, early 20th century, signed by Peter Newell",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in illustration] | \"Opposite to her was an old Sheep sitting in an arm-chair, knitting\" [caption below illustration]"
}

{
  "scene": "Two royal figures wearing crowns sit together examining or reading something (appears to be a book or document). The figure on the left is a queen-like character holding a small orb or ball, looking concerned. The figure on the right is a king with a feathered crown, leaning in to look at the item with a puzzled, unhappy expression. Both are dressed in ornate royal garments.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with soft tonal shading, characteristic of early 20th century book illustration. The style is whimsical and slightly caricatured, consistent with children's book illustration circa 1900-1920.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell (artist signature, lower left)\n\"The poor King looked puzzled and unhappy\" (caption below illustration)"
}

{
  "scene": "A rotund king wearing a pointed nightcap lies on his back asleep on the ground, mouth wide open in a snore. He holds a scepter loosely in his hands, and a small insect (grasshopper or cricket) perches on the top of the scepter. Leaves scatter in the background.",
  "style": "Pen and ink illustration with sepia/grayscale wash tones, characteristic of early 20th century book illustration style, signed by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell (artist signature, lower left)\n\"'It's only the Red King snoring'\" (caption below image)"
}

{
  "scene": "A small, round, doll-like figure wearing a crown and holding knitting needles is shown startled or frightened as a large ghostly hand reaches toward it with what appears to be a feather duster or cloth. The figure wears striped stockings and buckled shoes. The scene depicts someone about to dust a small character.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a whimsical, early 20th-century children's book style, consistent with American illustration circa 1900-1920. The artist signature reads 'Peter Newell', a well-known illustrator of that era.",
  "visible_text": "\"She thought she might as well dust him a little\" | Peter Newell (signature)"
}

{
  "scene": "A child or young person grabs and shakes a tall, elderly, long-nosed man wearing a top hat who is perched on a wooden fence or gate. The old man appears distressed. The setting is a rural outdoor scene with trees and wildflowers in the background.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with tonal wash, characteristic of late 19th to early 20th century book illustration. Signed by Peter Newell, a known American illustrator of that era (circa 1900s), likely from a Lewis Carroll 'Through the Looking-Glass' edition.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in image]\n\"'I shook him well from side to side,\nUntil his face was blue'\""
}

{
  "scene": "A chaotic battle scene showing armored soldiers (wearing helmets and carrying spears/pikes) stumbling, falling, and struggling to keep their footing on the ground. Horses and riders are also depicted tumbling. The soldiers appear comically clumsy, with many on hands and knees or falling over one another in a forest or dark battlefield setting.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a late Victorian/Edwardian style, likely early 1900s. The artist signature 'Newell' is visible, consistent with Peter Newell's illustration style used in editions of Lewis Carroll's Alice books.",
  "visible_text": "\"She had never seen soldiers so uncertain on their feet\"\nNewell"
}

{
  "scene": "A large, fearsome dragon-like creature (the Jabberwock) with wings, claws, bulging eyes, and an open mouth looms over a small child figure who stands in the lower right holding a sword. The forest floor is scattered with eye-like mushrooms or plants. The monster descends menacingly toward the child.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a detailed, expressive early 20th century book illustration style, consistent with Edwardian-era children's book art. Signed 'Peter New' in the upper right corner.",
  "visible_text": "Peter New [artist signature, upper right]\n\n\"The Jabberwock, with eyes of flame,\nCame whiffling through the tulgey wood,\nAnd burbled as it came!\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white pinafore dress (Alice) faces the Red Queen, an oddly proportioned regal figure wearing a crown and ornate robes, who points a finger at her. They stand outdoors on a path with hills and clouds in the background. The scene depicts the moment the Red Queen interrogates Alice.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash toning, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration style, circa early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature, lower right]\n\"'Where do you come from?' said the Red Queen\" [caption below illustration]"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress sits on the ground in a forest setting, looking up at an oversized anthropomorphized gnat perched on a twig above her. Wildflowers and foliage surround her. The gnat is depicted with exaggerated, almost human-like qualities.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash toning, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa early 1900s.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"While the Gnat was balancing itself on a twig\""
}

{
  "scene": "Anthropomorphized chess pieces walking about in pairs: a King and Queen (with crowns), two Rooks (bell-shaped), a Bishop (in white robes and mitre), a Knight (horse-headed figure in armor), and Pawns (small round figures on the ground). The chessmen are depicted as lively characters interacting with each other in a crowded scene.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash shading, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration (circa early 1900s), signed by Peter Newell, likely from an edition of Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass'.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell\n\"The chessmen were walking about, two and two!\""
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white dress with pinafore (Alice) sits on a fireplace mantelpiece, with a whimsical face clock to her left, a glass dome to her right, and a framed picture of a jester/harlequin on the wall behind. She appears to be near or passing through a looking glass. The setting is a Victorian drawing room.",
  "style": "Black and white halftone illustration, Victorian/Edwardian era book illustration style, realistic with slightly dreamlike quality, signed by Peter Newell (early 1900s)",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature bottom right]; \"In another moment Alice was through the glass\" [caption below illustration]"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a Victorian-style dress and apron (Alice) stands on a garden path, looking with surprise at a cluster of anthropomorphic talking flowers, including a Tiger-lily with a face, sunflowers with faces, and a rose with a face. The flowers appear to be speaking to her.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash shading, characteristic of late 19th to early 20th century book illustration. Signed by Peter Newell, consistent with his 1902 illustrated edition of 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature within illustration]\n\"'We can talk,' said the Tiger-lily\" [caption below illustration]"
}

{
  "scene": "Interior of a railway train compartment. A young girl in a white dress and decorated hat sits on a trunk on the left. A large bearded man in a top hat and white suit sits in the center, holding a cane with a ticket. Behind a partition, a monkey-like conductor peers over holding binoculars. A figure in checkered clothing is partially visible on the right.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash tones, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, circa 1900-1910. Whimsical and humorous in character, consistent with Lewis Carroll illustrations.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature, lower left]\n\"At last he said, 'You're travelling the wrong way'\""
}

{
  "scene": "Two characters on a beach: a weeping, elderly carpenter-like figure wearing an apron and sailor's cap, stooped over and holding a small handkerchief, alongside a large Walrus figure in striped trousers, both looking downward sorrowfully. Ocean waves and a rocky headland visible in background. Scene depicts the Walrus and the Carpenter from Lewis Carroll's 'Through the Looking-Glass.'",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash toning, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration, early 20th century. Signed by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [signature/artist credit]\n\"'If this were only cleared away,' They said, 'it would be grand!'\""
}

{
  "scene": "Two anthropomorphic horse-headed knights in armor, each mounted on horses, facing each other in a confrontational pose as if engaged in or about to engage in combat. The knights have exaggerated, cartoonish horse faces with wide eyes. One knight appears lighter in color, the other darker. Various equipment and bags hang from the saddles. A small figure or object is partially visible at the lower left.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink/graphite illustration in a whimsical, satirical style typical of early 20th century book illustration (circa 1900-1920). Signed by Peter Newell, a well-known American illustrator of that era.",
  "visible_text": "\"They began banging away at each other\" (caption below image); \"Peter Newell\" (artist's signature in lower right of illustration)"
}

{
  "scene": "Three figures seated on grass: a girl (Alice) in a white dress wearing a crown, flanked by two queen figures also wearing crowns. The figure on the right is a large, rotund, open-mouthed queen holding a scepter, wrapped in ornate robes. The figure on the left, seen from behind, is similarly robed. This depicts Alice with the Red Queen and White Queen from 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration in a detailed, realistic yet whimsical Victorian/Edwardian style, typical of early 20th century book illustration. Illustrated by Peter Newell.",
  "visible_text": "Peter Newell [artist signature in image]\n\"'She's in that state of mind,' said the White Queen, 'that she wants to deny something'\""
}

{
  "scene": "Three characters: the White Rabbit in a jacket holding papers, Alice (young girl with long dark hair and bow) looking on with hand raised to mouth in surprise, and the King of Hearts wearing a crown and royal robes holding a scepter, appearing to swoon or feel faint. The White Rabbit appears to be presenting something alarming to the King.",
  "style": "Black and white pen-and-ink illustration with wash shading, characteristic of late Victorian/Edwardian book illustration style, circa early 1900s. Signed by Peter Newell, known illustrator of Alice in Wonderland editions.",
  "visible_text": "\"'You alarm me!' said the King. 'I feel faint!'\" and artist signature 'Peter Newell' in lower right corner"
}

{
  "scene": "A chaotic banquet scene from Alice in Wonderland: Alice (seen from behind, wearing blue dress, white apron, striped stockings, and a golden crown) stands amid a tumultuous dinner party gone wrong. Giant insect-like creatures (rocking-horse flies or snap-dragon flies) swarm through the air. The table is overturned with food, dishes, candelabras, and various objects flying about. Fireworks or rockets streak across the upper sky. A red queen-like figure and other fantastical characters are visible in the chaos.",
  "style": "Victorian-era watercolor illustration, detailed and whimsical, consistent with late 19th or early 20th century book illustration style reminiscent of John Tenniel or Arthur Rackham's Alice in Wonderland artwork, with soft washes and intricate line work.",
  "visible_text": null
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl with blonde hair wearing a blue dress, white apron, and striped stockings rows a small wooden boat on a river or stream. Seated opposite her is a large anthropomorphic sheep wearing a white bonnet and shawl, holding knitting needles. In the background, a shop window is visible with silhouettes of various objects on shelves. This depicts Alice and the Sheep from 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "style": "Victorian-era watercolor illustration, consistent with John Tenniel's style for Lewis Carroll's Alice books, circa 1870s, with soft earthy tones and detailed character rendering typical of 19th-century book illustration.",
  "visible_text": "TEA (written in reverse/mirror writing on the shop window)"
}

{
  "scene": "A young girl in a white pinafore dress and blue striped stockings (Alice) stands looking up at an elderly knight in silver armor riding a white horse laden with various objects. The scene is set in a forest. The knight has an oversized, comical head and wears spurs. The horse carries bundles, carrots, and miscellaneous items. This depicts Alice and the White Knight from 'Through the Looking-Glass' by Lewis Carroll.",
  "style": "Victorian-era chromolithograph illustration, realistic yet whimsical watercolor style, likely late 19th century (1870s–1890s), consistent with illustrated editions of Lewis Carroll's works by artists such as John Tenniel or later colorized adaptations.",
  "visible_text": null
}

{
  "scene": "Alice (a young blonde girl in a white dress with a pinafore) stands looking upward at a large caterpillar perched atop a giant mushroom, smoking a hookah pipe. The caterpillar blows smoke rings into the air. The scene is from 'Alice's Adventures in Wonderland,' specifically the chapter featuring the Blue Caterpillar.",
  "style": "Watercolor illustration in an Edwardian/early 20th-century style, circa 1900–1920s, with soft warm tones and detailed, whimsical character rendering typical of period children's book illustration.",
  "visible_text": "A small monogram or publisher's mark in the lower right corner appearing to read 'LW' or similar initials within a decorative box, but no other legible text."
}

{
  "scene": "A small playing-card figure (a club suit card soldier/guard) dressed in white with a black clubs symbol, wearing a flat-topped hat and curled shoes, stands before a large, imposing king or royal figure in elaborate robes, armor helmet, and chains. They are in a garden setting with rose bushes and stone steps. The scene appears to be from Alice in Wonderland, likely depicting a card soldier before the King or a similar royal character.",
  "style": "Art Nouveau / Edwardian era illustration, circa 1900-1915, with rich watercolor or gouache technique, decorative linework, and ornate detailing typical of early 20th century children's book illustration. The monogram 'OLB' or 'ALB' appears in the top left corner in an Art Nouveau cartouche.",
  "visible_text": "ALB (or OLB) — monogram/initials in decorative cartouche, top left corner"
